 Lectureship in Industrial Sociology with Joe Banks at Liverpool, but it turned out to be on community, so withdrew.  Tried a job at Durham, which went to Robert Moore.
\par 
\par Then job advertised in Edinburgh.  Impressed by Tom Burns' work.  Fell in love at once with Edinburgh.  Offered the job, and in Edinburgh ever since.
\par 
\par Now very detached from the class debate.  Liked Bell and Newby on farmers, worked on petite bourgeoisie himself, but felt the debate had become less intellectually interesting.  Feels that the importance of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 The Affluent Worker}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 
 was to establish the Weberian approach to class in Britain, empirically: a Weberian approach which took Marx seriously, all the research group did.  Although John Rex also important.  Regrets advent of Althusser.
\par 
\par The social material in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 The Affluent Worker}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 
 also of lasting importance.  Frank wrote the chapter on friendship.  But the main thesis of the book is now dead, of no interest.  At the time, the political question mattered a lot.  Crosland's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 Must Labour Lose?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566  Was th
e trigger for the book.  But the debate on embourgeoisement is more alive.
\par 
\par Met Jean in Cambridge in 1959: born in Lerwick, read psychology in Aberdeen, Dip Ed, taught disturbed children at Crichton Royal Hospital in Dumfries, decided to become clinical ps
ychologist, course at Guys, then job at Cambridge.  Married in 1963, daughter born 1964, son Sean born 1966.  1970-96 worked at the Royal Hospital for Sick Children, looking after the Lothian clinical psychology service.  Resigned over re-organisation, cl
inical tutor for three years, now retired.
\par 
\par Cottage in Perthshire since 1970, grow own vegetables.  Frank has wide interested in music, classical, jazz, etc; Jean especially in folk music.  Ran local Folk Club together.
\par 
\par Does not think living with a psychol
ogist has influenced him.  She is not theoretical: says she is retail and he is wholesale.  But does accept there are psychological processes.  Their joint interest in theatre is a more important influence, in heightening awareness of interactive processe
s.  Has much sympathy for Goffman.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272 
