\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 
Came to Edinburgh Department of Sociology the same year as his old friend and research colleague Brian Elliott: a Londoner, he had read anthropology in Edinburgh, lectured in Glasgow.
  Other colleagues Jan Poggi, theoretician, hired by Tom Burns at a railway station, spoke English as fast as Italian.  Rosemary Johnson, social psychologist, very bright, great teacher, but never wrote. Frank had to teach first year onwards sociology tut
orials, and second year statistics.
\par 
\par Tom Burns very far-seeing.  Chose some very idiosyncratic books for courses.  Brought in Ton}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5261288 y}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566  Coxon and Charles Jones for methods.  Tom profoundly well-read and imaginative, many continental links, theoretical and empiri
cal, a polymath.  Also very ahead in introducing student feedback.  Created a very collegiate department.  Nearly all of those he hired either have Personal Chairs, or went to Chairs in other universities.  Tom passed through 1968 era without upheavals, b
ecause he was always leading change himself, strategy of permanent revolution.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 The Management of Innovation}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566  is a book still well worth reading (did he invent Stalker?).  Took teaching exceptionally seriously.  Early appreciation of Goffman.  His BBC book a
lso interesting, published despite their opposition.  Terrific inaugural lecture.  Could be infuriating, but a great department-builder.  Believed academics should also be good citizens. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3429636 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566  
\par Friendly with Brian Elliott, decided to work together on class, saw that the middle class had been little studied (except C. Wright Mills): focus on a marginal group to see how the structure keeps things apart - and chose small shopkeepers. 
\par  
\par Big survey in Edinburgh.  Used new computer methods.  Brian introduced area and ecological perspectives.  Also collected qualitative data, and used it a little more than in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 The Affluent Worker}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 .
\par 
\par For }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 The Affluent Worker}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 
 qualitative data included some pure observation in plants, and material from interviews on people's images of class. No life stories, no fieldwork journals.
\par 
\par Also collecting material of images from shopkeepers.  Remembers walking round George Square with Brian, more and more satisfied with the idea of marginality, moving to idea of petite bourgeoisie.
\par \tab 
\par Some of the qualitative material was written up in the book on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 The Petite Bourgeoisie }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 (1981), which also included European contributions.  Discussions in a twice-yearly ESRC group seminar on social class.  Chapter in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 Annual Review of Sociology.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 
But many sociologists had no interest at all in the lower middle class.  Their research was picked on later when research on small business took off, with Goffee and Scase.  So although not originally topical in
 a political sense, the research became so in retrospect.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272 
