\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 David McCrone had now join
ed them, and with Brian they decided in the early 1980s to investigate petit bourgeois social movements, such as the Freedom Association and the National Federation of Small Enterpr}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5261288 ises.  Interviewing these right-}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 wing but sometimes anarchical people.  Some
 anthropological work but little had been written about them.  Developed a technique of two interviewing together, one taking notes, the other questioning, but reversing roles in turns: has written a paper on this.  Also interviewed some right-wing politi
cians, such as Theresa Gorman, believed in privatising the police.  Employed Stuart Black to do some of the interviews, but Frank also did a lot of them.
\par   
\par Then Brian went to Canada, and at the same time, mid-1980s, with Dave, moved into new field, the soc
ial structure of Scotland.  Had been very close colleague with Brian.  He was also an actor and also liked the hills.  They were complementary, Brian wrote more easily (paper and pencil), Frank more methodological.   They always built secretaries into the
i
r research funding.  Never had a paper turned down.  Good friends and it worked.  Brian tended to undertake too much, rewrite too much.  Very pleasant, witty, cultured.  Family orientated, and the two families got on well.  It was a wrench when Brian went
, and Frank missed him.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272 
