\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid16344321 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16344321\charrsid16344321 
The Sociography of Scotland and Scottish Identity
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12397272 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16344321 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 
David McCrone had already become his research partner.  He can be impatient and brusque.  Story of coming back from ESRC class group meeting at a station buffet, Dave furious when i
gnored by buffet girl, stormed out.  But mellower now, got on extremely well.  Scottish, from Aberdeenshire.  He was writing on Scotland.
\par 
\par Meanwhile late 1980s, with Mike Anderson (social and economic history), Bob Morris (sociology), Brian May (economist)
 and Steve Kendrick (unfortunate researcher), successfully bid for ESRC Social Change and Economic Life initiative, huge project co-ordinated by Duncan Gallie.  Terrific dataset, the product of much heated argument, fighting for space.  Frank co-ordinatin
g the Edinburgh team, too much time on trains to meetings.
\par 
\par In 1986-7 left Sociology to set up Research Centre for Social Sciences.  Had been teaching 20 years, wanted a change.  Aim to pull together some research, and to get new research going.  Hired Robi
n Williams, now director, for programme on information and communication technologies; and then the Social Change and Economic Life project.  This was mainly survey-based, but some in-depth work on firms, management buy-outs, not a success.
\par 
\par Became interested in qualitative sub-sample of a sample survey, began to see the power of such an approach.  Now recording interviews, fully transcribed, machine-aided analysis, NuDist, Eudora, etc.
\par 
\par New work with Dave on Scottish class and identity started with the Arts and Landed Elites study, funded by }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4721092 ESRC, with Richard}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4721092\charrsid4721092  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4721092 Kiely}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4721092\charrsid2513566  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12397272\charrsid2513566 and Robert Stewart as research officers.  All qualitative.
\par 
\par Then - again with much thought to research design -decided on study of Berwick-upon-Tweed as a marginal case, ambiguous identity.  Funded by Leverhulme.  Interviewing by }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6646431 Richard K}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4721092 iely}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
